'1:2': [
{sup:1, word:"those", lines:["The first group of New Testament believers, composed of those who were with the Savior during His ministry on earth."]},
{sup:"a", word:"eyewitnesses", vrefs:"2&nbsp;Pet. 1:16; 1&nbsp;John 1:1-3; Acts 1:3; 4:20"},
{sup:2, word:"ministers", lines:["Lit., servants; i.e., official servants, apparitors, who attend or serve an officer or authority to carry out his orders. The Greek word is used in {Luk4:20|4:20}; {Mat5:25|Matt. 5:25}; {Mrk14:54|Mark 14:54}; {Act26:16|Acts 26:16}; and {1Co4:1|1&nbsp;Cor. 4:1}."]},
{sup:3, word:"word", lines:["The word of the gospel, ministered and preached to people ({Act6:4|Acts 6:4}; {Act8:4|8:4})."]},
{sup:4, word:"delivered", lines:["This indicates that the writer of this Gospel was not among those disciples who were with the Savior during His earthly life."]},
],
'1:3': [
{sup:1, word:"me", lines:["The early church recognized Luke as the author of both this Gospel and the Acts. Luke&rsquo;s authorship is evident from the style of composition of the two books. Luke was a Gentile ({Col4:14|Col. 4:14}; cf. {Col4:11|Col. 4:11}), probably an Asiatic Greek, and a physician ({Col4:14|Col. 4:14}). Beginning in Troas, he joined Paul in his ministry and accompanied him in his last three ministry journeys ({Act16:10|Acts 16:10}-{Act16:17|17}; {Act20:5|20:5}&mdash;{Act21:18|21:18}; {Act27:1|27:1}&mdash;{Act28:15|28:15}). He was a faithful companion of Paul until Paul&rsquo;s martyrdom ({Phm1:24|Philem. 24}; {2Ti4:11|2&nbsp;Tim. 4:11}). Hence, his Gospel should represent Paul&rsquo;s views, as Mark&rsquo;s represents Peter&rsquo;s (see {Mrk1:1^1P1|note 1<sup>1</sup>, par. 1}, in {Mrk1|Mark 1}).","The Gospels of Luke, Matthew, and Mark are synoptic in regard to the Savior&rsquo;s humanity (see {Mrk1:1^1P2|note 1<sup>1</sup>, par. 2}, in {Mrk1|Mark 1}). Luke&rsquo;s Gospel reveals God among men in His saving grace given to fallen mankind. Its purpose is to present the Savior as a genuine, normal, and perfect man. It gives a complete genealogy of the man Jesus, from His parents back to Adam, the first generation of mankind, and shows that He is a genuine descendant of man&mdash;a son of man (see {Mat1:1^1P2|note 1<sup>1</sup>, pars. 2} and {Mat1:1^1P3|3}, in {Mat1|Matt. 1}). Its record of the life of this man impresses us with the completeness and perfection of His humanity. Hence, this Gospel stresses the Lord as the Man-Savior. Based on the moral principles that apply to all men, it presents gospel messages, as in {Luk4:16|4:16}-{Luk4:21|21}; {Luk7:41|7:41}-{Luk7:43|43}; {Luk12:14|12:14}-{Luk12:21|21}; and {Luk13:2|13:2}-{Luk13:5|5}; gospel parables, as in {Luk10:30|10:30}-{Luk10:37|37}; {Luk14:16|14:16}-{Luk14:24|24}; {Luk15:3|15:3}-{Luk15:32|32}; and {Luk18:9|18:9}-{Luk18:14|14}; and gospel cases, as in {Luk7:36|7:36}-{Luk7:50|50}; {Luk13:10|13:10}-{Luk13:17|17}; {Luk16:19|16:19}-{Luk16:31|31}; {Luk19:1|19:1}-{Luk19:10|10}; and {Luk23:39|23:39}-{Luk23:43|43}. None of these are recorded in the other Gospels. In contrast to Matthew, Luke does not stress the dispensational aspect or the Jewish background. It is the Gospel written to mankind in general, and it announces the good news to all people ({Luk2:10|2:10}). Its characteristic is absolutely not Jewish but Gentile ({Luk4:25|4:25}-{Luk4:28|28}). It is a Gospel to all sinners, both Jewish and Gentile. As such, the sequence of its record is according to morality, not according to historical events. See notes {Mat8:16^1P2|16<sup>1</sup>, par. 2}, in {Mat8|Matt. 8} and {Mrk14:20^1|20<sup>1</sup>} in {Mrk14|Mark 14}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"orderly", vrefs:"Acts 11:4"},
{sup:"b", word:"excellent", vrefs:"Acts 23:26; 24:3; 26:25"},
{sup:"2c", word:"Theophilus", vrefs:"Acts 1:1", lines:["The Greek word means loved by God, or friend of God. Probably a Gentile believer who occupied some official position under the Roman Empire."]},
],
