'1:6': [
{sup:1, word:"they", lines:["They were among God&rsquo;s chosen people and had been preserved in the custody of the law in the Old Testament and brought forth by it to be useful to God for the initiation of the gospel in the New Testament."]},
{sup:"2a", word:"righteous", vrefs:"Luke 1:75; 2:25; Gen. 7:1", lines:["This does not contradict {Rom3:20|Rom. 3:20}. Here it means to be right, i.e., blameless, in the sight of God according to the Old Testament commandments and ordinances ({Luk2:25|2:25}; {Phi3:6|Phil. 3:6}). It does not mean that these righteous ones were not sinful, without sin and sins. They were blameless, but not without blemish. They still needed the unblemished sin and trespass offerings in type ({Lev4:28|Lev. 4:28}; {Lev5:15|5:15}) for their expiation that they might have contact with God."]},
{sup:"3b", word:"walking", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Kings 9:4; Psa. 119:1", lines:["I.e., living according to."]},
{sup:4, word:"ordinances", lines:["The Old Testament law is generally called &ldquo;the law&rdquo;; its contents are divided into three categories: commandments, statutes, and ordinances. Commandments, as God&rsquo;s basic commands, are the general principles of the law. There are ten commandments ({Exo20:2|Exo. 20:2}-{Exo20:17|17}). Statutes, or laws, regulations, set forth, explain in detail, and supplement the commandments, as recorded in {Exo20:22|Exo. 20:22}-{Exo20:26|26}. Ordinances, like statutes, set forth, explain in detail, and supplement the commandments, and, in addition, include verdicts, as recorded in {Exo21:1|Exo. 21:1}&mdash;{Exo23:19|23:19}. Ordinances minus the verdicts become statutes. The Greek word for ordinances here is the same as that in {Rom2:26|Rom. 2:26} and in {Heb9:1|Heb. 9:1}, {Heb9:10|10}."]},
{sup:"c", word:"blameless", vrefs:"Phil. 3:6"},
],
