'10:29': [
{sup:1, word:"justify", lines:["He must have been one of the self-justified Pharisees ({Luk16:14|16:14}-{Luk16:15|15}; {Luk18:9|18:9}-{Luk18:10|10})."]},
],
'10:30': [
{sup:1, word:"certain", lines:["This is one of the parables narrated only by Luke. It conveys the principle of high morality in the Savior&rsquo;s full salvation. The Savior intended the &ldquo;certain man&rdquo; to be a figure of the self-justified lawyer ({Luk10:29|v. 29}) as a sinner who had fallen from the foundation of peace (Jerusalem) to the condition of curse (Jericho)."]},
{sup:2, word:"down", lines:["Indicating a fall from the city of the foundation of peace to the city of curse."]},
{sup:3, word:"Jerusalem", lines:["Jerusalem means foundation of peace (cf. {Heb7:2|Heb. 7:2}); Jericho was a city of curse ({Jos6:26|Josh. 6:26}; {1Ki16:34|1&nbsp;Kings 16:34})."]},
{sup:"3a", word:"Jericho", vrefs:"Josh. 16:1; Luke 18:35", lines:["See {Luk10:30^3|note 30<sup>3</sup>}."]},
{sup:4, word:"robbers", lines:["Signifying the legalistic teachers of the Judaic law ({Joh10:1|John 10:1}), who used the law ({1Co15:56|1&nbsp;Cor. 15:56}) to rob lawkeepers such as the self-justified lawyer."]},
{sup:5, word:"stripped", lines:["Signifying the stripping caused by the Judaistic teachers&rsquo; misuse of the law."]},
{sup:6, word:"beaten", lines:["Lit., laid blows upon; signifying the killing by the law ({Rom7:9|Rom. 7:9}-{Rom7:10|10})."]},
{sup:7, word:"leaving", lines:["Signifying that the Judaistic teachers left the lawkeeper in a dead condition ({Rom7:11|Rom. 7:11}, {Rom7:13|13})."]},
],
'10:31': [
{sup:1, word:"priest", lines:["The one who should have cared for God&rsquo;s people by teaching them the law of God ({Deu33:10|Deut. 33:10}; {2Ch15:3|2&nbsp;Chron. 15:3}) was going down on the same road and was thus unable to render any help to the beaten one."]},
],
'10:32': [
{sup:1, word:"Levite", lines:["One of those who helped God&rsquo;s people in their worship to God ({Num1:50|Num. 1:50}; {Num3:6|3:6}-{Num3:7|7}; {Num8:19|8:19}) was coming to the same place, and he too was unable to render any help to the dying one."]},
],
'10:33': [
{sup:"1a", word:"Samaritan", vrefs:"Matt. 10:5", lines:["Signifying the Man-Savior, who apparently was a layman of low estate. He was despised and slandered as a low and mean Samaritan ({Joh8:48|John 8:48}; {Joh4:9|4:9} and {Joh4:9^1|note 1}) by the self-exalted and self-justified Pharisees, including the one to whom He was speaking here (vv. {Luk10:25|25}, {Luk10:29|29}). Such a Man-Savior, in His lost-one-seeking and sinner-saving ministry journey ({Luk19:10|19:10}), came down to the place where the wounded victim of the Judaistic robbers lay in his miserable and dying condition. When He saw him, He was moved with compassion in His humanity with His divinity and rendered him tender healing and saving care, fully meeting his urgent need (vv. {Luk10:34|34}-{Luk10:35|35})."]},
{sup:"b", word:"compassion", vrefs:"Matt. 9:36; 14:14; 15:32; 20:34; Mark 1:41"},
],
'10:34': [
{sup:"1a", word:"bound", vrefs:"Isa. 1:6", lines:["In vv. {Luk10:34|34}-{Luk10:35|35} all the aspects of the good Samaritan&rsquo;s care for the dying one portray the Man-Savior in His merciful, tender, and bountiful care, in His humanity with His divinity, for a sinner condemned under law, showing to the uttermost His high standard of morality in His saving grace: (1) He bound up his wounds&mdash;healing him; (2) He poured oil and wine on his wounds&mdash;giving him the Holy Spirit and the divine life ({Mat9:17|Matt. 9:17} and {Mat9:17^1|note 1}; {Joh2:9|John 2:9} and {Joh2:9^1|note 1}); (3) He placed him on his own beast (a donkey)&mdash;carrying him by lowly means in a lowly way ({Zec9:9|Zech. 9:9}); (4) He brought him to an inn&mdash;bringing him to the church; (5) He took care of him&mdash;taking care of him through the church; (6) He paid the inn for him&mdash;blessing the church on his behalf; (7) He said that he would repay at his return whatever the inn spent&mdash;declaring that whatever the church spends in this age on one who is saved by the Lord will be repaid at the Savior&rsquo;s coming back."]},
],
'10:35': [
{sup:"1a", word:"denarii", vrefs:"Matt. 18:28", lines:["See {Joh6:7^1|note 7<sup>1</sup>} in {Joh6|John 6}."]},
],
'10:36': [
{sup:1, word:"become", lines:["The self-justified lawyer thought that he could love another as his neighbor ({Luk10:29|v. 29}), not knowing, under the blindness of self-justification, that he himself needed a neighbor, the Man-Savior, to love him."]},
],
'10:37': [
{sup:1, word:"The", lines:["Or, The one who dealt mercifully with him. The self-justified one was helped to know that he needed a loving neighbor (such as the good Samaritan, who was a figure of the Man-Savior) to love him, not a neighbor for him to love. The Savior intended to unveil to him through this story (1) that he was condemned to death under the law and was unable to take care of himself, much less love others, and (2) that the Man-Savior was the One who would love him and render him full salvation."]},
],
'10:38': [
{sup:1, word:"village", lines:["Bethany ({Joh12:1|John 12:1} and {Joh12:1^1|note 1}; {Mrk11:1|Mark 11:1}; {Mat21:17|Matt. 21:17} and {Mat21:17^1|note 1})."]},
{sup:"2a", word:"Martha", vrefs:"John 11:1, 19-20; 12:2", lines:["Probably from Aramaic, meaning she was rebellious."]},
{sup:"b", word:"received", vrefs:"Luke 19:6"},
],
'10:39': [
{sup:1, word:"Mary", lines:["Gk. Maria for Heb. Miriam, meaning their rebellion ({Num12:1|Num. 12:1}, {Num12:10|10}-{Num12:15|15}). The meaning of Martha and Mary conveys the thought of rebellion, perhaps pointing to the natural life of Martha and Mary. The Lord&rsquo;s salvation can transform the rebellious into the submissive, as portrayed in this story. One like the rebellious Miriam in the Old Testament becomes one like the submissive Mary in the New Testament."]},
{sup:"a", word:"feet", vrefs:"Deut. 33:3; Luke 8:35"},
],
'10:40': [
{sup:"1a", word:"being", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Cor. 7:35", lines:["Meaning to be drawn around in different directions."]},
],
'10:41': [
{sup:"a", word:"anxious", vrefs:"Matt. 6:25-34; Phil. 4:6"},
],
'10:42': [
{sup:"a", word:"one", vrefs:"Psa. 27:4"},
{sup:"1b", word:"good", vrefs:"Psa. 16:5", lines:["The Lord prefers that His saved ones who love Him listen to Him ({Luk10:39|v. 39}) that they may know His desire, rather than do things for Him without knowing His will (cf. {1Sa15:22|1&nbsp;Sam. 15:22}; {Ecc5:1|Eccl. 5:1}).","It is quite significant that this story of Martha and Mary immediately follows the parable of the good Samaritan. The parable shows the compassion and love of the Savior, who is a man and becomes the sinners&rsquo; neighbor; the story of Martha and Mary unveils the desire and preference of the Lord, who is God and becomes the believers&rsquo; Master. The Savior gives us His compassion and love so that we can be saved by Him; the Lord expresses His desire and preference so that we can serve Him. After receiving salvation from the Savior, we should render service to the Lord. For our salvation we need to realize the Savior&rsquo;s compassion and love; for our service we need to know the Lord&rsquo;s desire and preference."]},
],
